<graph edgedefault="directed"><node id="doc:tmp_1771604354512_aiclab1_1">
  <data key="d0">DOCUMENT</data>
  <data key="d1">tmp_1771604354512_aiclab1_1</data>
  <data key="d2">LAB 1
EXPERIMENT 1: RC COUPLED COMMON EMITTER AMPLIFIER USING
BC547
AIM - To design and study a single stage RC coupled common emitter amplifier
using a BC547 transistor and to determine its voltage gain, input impedance = 2 kΩ,
frequency response, and bandwidth using a sine wave input signal.
APPARATUS REQUIRED -
1. Regulated DC power supply
2. Functiongenerator
3. CRO / DSO
4. multimeter
5. Breadboard
6. Connectingwires
7. BC547 transistor
8. Resistors and capacitors
THEORY -
 An RC coupled amplifier is a voltage amplifier in which resistors and capacitors
are used to couple the AC signal from input to output while blocking DC
components. The coupling capacitors prevent DC from one stage affecting the
biasing of another stage.
 In a common emitter amplifier, the emitter terminal is common to both input and
output. The input signal is applied at the base and the output is taken from the
collector. This configuration provides high voltage gain and introduces a phase
inversion of 180 degrees between input and output.
 The transistor is biased using a voltage divider bias network. This keeps the
transistor operating in the active region so that a small change in base voltage
causes a large change in collector current. The collector resistor converts these
current variations into voltage variations, producing amplification.
 When a sine wave signal is applied at the input, it causes variations in base
current. These variations produce larger variations in collector current, resulting
in an amplified output signal at the collector.
pg.1-I
24BEC064

 The gain of an RC coupled amplifier depends on frequency.At low frequencies,
the reactance of coupling and bypass capacitors is high, reducing gain. At mid
frequencies, the gain remains nearly constant. At high frequencies, gain
decreases due to internal transistor capacitances and the Miller effect.
PROCEDURE –
1. Assemble the RC coupled common emitter amplifier circuit on a breadboard
as per the circuit diagram.
2. Apply a DC supply voltage of 15 V to the circuit.
3. Connect the function generator to the input through the coupling capacitor.
4. Apply a sine wave input of 500 mV peak-to-peak.
5. Observe the input and output waveforms on the CRO.
6. Measure the output peak-to-peak voltage.
7. Vary the input frequency from low to high.
8. Record the output voltage at each frequency.
9. Switch off the power supply after completing the experiment.
pg.1-II
24BEC064

COMPONENTS USED –
Component Value
Transistor BC547
Collector resistor 1.5 kΩ
Emitter resistor 1 kΩ
Base resistor R1 100 kΩ
Base resistor R2 18 kΩ
Input capacitor 1 µF
Output capacitor 1 µF
Emitter bypass capacitor 22 µF
Supply voltage 12 V
Parameter Value
Signaltype Sine wave
Input voltage 500 mV p-p
Frequency range 1 Hz – 10 MHz
OBSERVATION TABLE -
